{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280602012/1937091901/0713.xml":{"full_text":"I FINANCIAL AND CLASSIFIED I-1\nClassified Ads \u00a3^r'f \u00a3>_ CyLt T?\nI p)t Jimntfcuj pto Part Four E\nPart 4~16 p*8e\u00bbWASHINGTON, D. C., SUNDAY MORNING, SEPTEMBER 19, 1937.\nD. C. STORE SALES\nSHARPLY IN WEEK\nVolumes Up 33.79 Per Cent\nFrom Previous Period,\nTop 1936 Marks.\nCHECKS AND BUILDING\nALSO REGISTER GAINS\nAccountants to Hear Nelson Mil\nler at Dinner Opening Season\nWednesday Evening.\nBY EDWARD C. STONE.\nWith the advent of cooler weather\nduring the past week. Washington re\ntail trade scored an increase of 33.79\nper cent over the previous five-day\nweek and a jump of 9.29 per cent over\nthe corresponding week a year ago,\nthe Commerce Department reported\nyesterday. These gains were far ahead\nof most of the 37 cities covered in the\nWeekly review.\nBank clearings in the Capital were\nalso better than a year ago. $23,729,652,\ncomparing with $23,159,494. Building\npermits in the District reached $815,\n000 and Included a $320,000 public\n\u2022chool building, standing out against\nthe $342,900 total of the previous week.\nTrade in the rest of the fifth reserve\ndistrict continued to increase. Balti\nmore, Richmond. Norfolk and other\ncities reporting substantial improve\nment over the same week last year.\nOpening of the schools was noted as\nan important factor in the decided\nbusiness upturn. In wholesale markets\nuncertainties in prices of cotton tex\ntiles are causing considerable \u201chand\nto-mouth buying.\"\nThe quick response of shoppers to\nthe crisp Pall weather is expected to\ncontinue and further brighten the\nSeptember trade picture.\nAccountants to Open Year.\nWith Nelson A. filler, assistant\nehief. Marketing Research Division.\nDepartment of Commerce, as principal\napeaker, Washington Chapter. National\nAssociation of\nCost Accountants,\nwill open the\n1937-38 season at\nthe H a m i 11\nHotel next Wed\nnesday evening,\nstarting with a\ndinner session.\nMr. Miller, who\nwill discuss \u201cDe\npartmental Ac\ncounting In Drug\n6tores,\u201d has had\nextensive experi\nence in both re\ntail and whole\nsale distribution, N*l,on A' Min'r'\nhas been with the Commerce Depart\nment since 1928 and has done much\nWriting on cost studies.\nThe forum discussion will be led by\nW. H. Meserole, Commerce Der>art\nmem business specialist and former\nstatistician for the American Relief\nAdministration, the program conclud\ning with the installation of chapter\nofficers.\nC. Milton C'ark is to be succeeded\nas president by Walter F. Raymond,\nchief auditor of the Griffith Con\neumers Co. Vice president will be\nWilliam Lee Slattery, controller of the\nPost Office Department, and George D.\nLane of the Felt Tarrant Manu\nfacturing Co. John L. Mitchell of the\nShannon Luchs Co. is secretary,\nand the treasurer is J. M. McLeod of\nthe Standard Engineering Co.\nDirectors for the coming year are\nOscar D. Crockett of Judd Det\nweiler, Inc.; George E. Davis, Fruit\nGrowers' Express Co.: B E. Hunsinger\nBenjamin Franklin University; Rob\nert W. King of the Farm Credit\nAdministration; O\u2019Neal M. Johnson.\nInternational Association of Ice Cream\nManufacturers. James B. May, South\nern Dairies, Inc., and William S.\nRitnour of National Fertilizer Asso\nciation.\nJoins District Acacia Staff.\nAppointment of Harry V. Hayden,\nJr., as a representative in the District\nof Columbia branch, was announced\nyesterday by the Acacia Mutual Life\nInsurance Co.\nA native of\nWashington, h e\nformerly was\nsecretary to the\ngrand commander\nof the Scottish\nRite Supreme\nCouncil; served\nas secretary to\nfour different\nchairmen of the\nRepublican Na\ntional Committee,\nand was engaged\nin the seed busi\nness here for sev\neral years. H*rry v H,yd*n- 3r\nHis most recent connection wa:\nwith the Federal Home Loan BanV\nBoard as assistant to the chairman\nassistant to the vice chairman an<\nadministrative assistant to the con\ntroller of the Home Owners\u2019 Loai\nCorp.\nMr. Hayden has held several office\nIn the Masonic Fraternity and Order o\nthe Eastern Star.\nMore Dividends Declared.\nDirectors of the Security Storage C(\nhave declared the quarterly dividen\nof *1.25 a share on the capital stocl\npayable October 11 to stockholders c\nrecord October 6, it was announce\nyesterday.\nThe Sun-Nap-Pak Manufacturin\nCo. has declared the regular dividen\n\u00abn Us preferred stock, payable Octobt\n1 to stockholders of record Septembf\n20. The usual dividend of 10 cem\nquarterly was also declared on tt\ncommon stock, payable on the san\ndates. Both stocks are quite wide!\nheld here.\nOn the Washington Stock Exchans\nyesterday the new Washington Gi\nLight preferred was again in deman\nthrea 10-share sales being registered i\n99. The stock closed with 98'3 b\nand 99*4 asked. Washington Railws\nA Electric figured in three sales i\nnow.\n\u25a0t\nCUT IN COPPER TALKED\nAS FOREIGN PRICE SAGS\nDomestic Reduction Seen as Possibility\nWith Electrolytic Abroad Selling at\n13.05 Cents Per Pound.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK. September 18.\u2014Rela\ntive weakness in foreign copper mar\nkets featured non-ferrous metals last\nweek, as electrolytic abroad sold at\n13.05 cents a pound, c.i.f. European\nbase ports.\nDomestic Valley price held un\nchanged at 14 cents a pound, but\nthere were rumors of a possible re\nduction because of the foreign de\nvelopments. Second hands offered\nlarger amounts as the week closed\nthe equivalent of 13.62 cents a\npound.\nThe market upset was due mainly\nto the bearish world statistics for Au\ngust. which showed a substantial in\ncrease in production and stocks and\na marked falling off in consumption.\nZinc remained unchanged, but the\ntone was easier on lower foreign mar\nkets and reports foreign metal was\ncurrently available at the equiva\nlent of 7 cents, duty paid, Atlantic\nand Gulf ports, against the domestic\nbase of 7 Vi cents a pound.\nTin advanced early with reports\nof competition between American ard\nJapanese buyers in the East for sup\nplies, but reacted later in sympa\nthy with the copper situation.\nLead trade marked time and\nwatched the events in neighboring\nmarkets. Current demand has be*'n\nlight and confined mostly to carload\namounts for September delivery.\n\u201cSQUEEZE\u201d ENDED,\nCORN DROPS FULL\nLIMIT OF 8 CENTS\nBreak in Deadlock Brings\nRumors of Compromise\nBetween Groups.\nBY FRANKLIN MULLIN,\nAssociated Press Marset Editor.\nCHICAGO. September 18. The\n\"squeeze\" in September corn collapsed\nI today, threats of a \"corner\" evapo\nj rated, and the price fell pfecipitously\nas far as it could go in one session\u2014\n8 cents a bushel.\nThe break came In the last 15 min\nutes, when the price tumbled to\n$1.04 exactly 12 cents below the\nhigh reached yesterday when the\n\"squeeze\u201d tvas at its peak.\nBreaking of the deadlock between\nowners of corn, or \u201clongs,\" and specu\nlative sellers committed to deliver, or\n\"shorts,\" was accompanied by a flood\nof gossip that a \u201ccompromise\u201d be\ntween the two groups had been\nreached, either at the insistence of\nBoard of Trade and Commodity Ex\nchange officials or because of the\nwillingness of \"longs\" to permit\n\"shorts\" to get out of the maiket at\nnot too great loss. There were re\nports also that freer offerings of old\ncorn from the country and possibly\nthat some new corn may be available\nfor delivery influenced longs to dump\ntheir holdings and take their profit.\nPit gossip credited one of the big\ngest grain merchandising organiza\ntions in the country With being the\nprincipal \"long.\u201d A leading corn pit\ntrader and a group of followers, to\ngether with a producers\u2019 co-operative,\nwere understood to comprise the\n\"short\" interest, but no confirmation\n1 of this could be obtained.\nOther pits in the exchange were\nquiet. Wheat started higher in sym\npathy with Liverpool strength, but\nlater eased to a lower close, largely\nreflecting weakness in cornered securi\nj ties.\nAt the close corn was varying from\nI unchanged to 8',- cents below Pri\n<See GRAIN, Page E-2.)\n\nDIVIDEND MEETINGS\nSCHEDULED TOMORROW\nB* the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, September 18.\u2014Divi\ndend meetings scheduled for Monday\ninclude Brooklyn-Manhattan Transit,\nCarolina, Chnchfield Ohio Railway;\nCudahy Packing Co., National Malle\ni able Steel Castings, Sheaffer Pen\ni and Spicer Manufacturing,\ni On Tuesday Atlas Corp. directors\nwill meet for dividend action.\nSet for Wednesday are meetings of\nUnited States Smelting. Alaska Jur.eau\nGold Mining, Cluett-Peabody, Na\ntional Distillers and Zenith Radio.\n\nEXPRESS TRAFFIC RISES.\nNEW YORK September 18 (A3).\u2014\nExpress traffic in July increased 5.26\nper cent over that for the similar pe\nriod of 1936, the Railway Express\nAgency reported today. An estimated\ntotal of 9.757.902 shipments was moved\nnearly 500,000 more than In July last\nI year.\n\nCOTTON IRREGULAR\nRAINS PREDICTED\nHedge Selling Encounters\nActive Trade Demand\nand Covering.\nfc.r the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, September 18.\u2014Cot\nton fluctuated over a narrow range\nj today, with increased Southern hedge\nselling again encountering fairly active\ntrade demand and week end covering.\nAfter December had eased from 8.76\nto 8.71, it turned steadier to close at\n8.74. Final prices were 1 point net\nhigher to 1 lower.\nThe market opened unchanged to 2\nhigher, but the easier tone of the\nstock market brought in some local\nselling and several deliveries regis\ntered further new lows for the move\nment. Continued foreign and domes\ntic trade price fixing, however, im\nparted considerable resistance. To\nI ward the close some covering developed\non the outlook for showers or rains\nnext week.\nNext week\u2019s forecast was for rain\nj in the Eastern belt at the beginning\nj of the week and showers in Central\ni and Western sections, commencing\nalong the Gulf Coast and becoming\nmore general toward the end of the\nweek. Amount of cotton on ship\nboard awaiting clearance at close of\nweek was estimated at 95,000 bales,\nagainst 71.000 last year and 55,000 two\nyears ago.\nThe range follows'.\n_ High. Low. Last.\nOctober _ 8.a; 8.8i s.8t;-87'\n[December _ 8.70 8.71 8.74-73\nJanuary _ 8.81 8.TH 8.78\nMarch _ 8.SKI 8.85 8.87-88\nMay '_9.00 8.1*5 8.98\nJuly 9.0!) 9.04 9.07-09\nSpot steady; middling. 9.00.\nCottonseed Oil.\nCottonseed oil moved within narrow\nlimits today. Toe undertone was steady\non a little covering for over the week end,\npromoted by the steadiness of cotton and\nlard. Crude was steadier, with sales at\ncents in the Southeast.\nFinal prices were 1 lower to 2 net\nhigher, with sales of 58 contracts Bleach\nable spot, nominal; October closed 7.39;\nDecember. 7.43: January, 7.14; March.\n7.4b, and May, 7.55.\nNew Orleans Prices.\nNEW ORLEANS September 18 UP).\u2014\nCotton futures closed steady, net 1 point\nhigher to 3 points lower.\nOpen. High. Low. Close.\nOctober _. 8.83 8.55 8.Mil 8.83-84\nDecember 8.83 8.85 8.81 8.84-bo\nJanuary _ 8.88 H.89 8.88 8.89\nMarch _8.90 8.97 8.91 8.90\nMay 9.ini 9.01) 9.03 9.yo\nJuly 9.13 9.14 9.08 9 13\nj October. 1938 9.33 9.33 9.33 9.24b-25a\nb\u2014Bid. a\u2014Asked.\nCottonseed oil closed steady. Bleachable\nprime Summer yellow 7.70 nominal. Prime\ncrude. tt.00-fl.13V September, 0.80b: Oc\ntober, h.Oob: December, 11.90b: January,\ntj.93b: March. 7.01 b. b\u2014Bid.\n\nPHILADELPHIA PRODUCE.\nPHILADELPHIA. September 18 UP/,\u2014\nLive poultry Fowl Plymouth Rock, fancy.\n37-38. ordinary. 20: mixed colors, fancy.\n30-37; Leghorns, extra fancy. 71. fancy,\ni 19-30: average. 10-18; Spring chickens,\ncrosses. 38-30. Red Springers, small, 37\n38; ducks White Pekin, fancy. 18-3 11 old\nj ducks. White Pekin, 17-30: Muscovy\nI White. 10-17\nDressed poultry unchanged.\nButter\u2014Top grades 36\",4-40: 93 score,\n35>4-3tt: 91. 35\nEggs\u2014Close firm. 3 890 cases. XJ. 8\nstandards. Nos. 1 and 3. 37-38V Nos. 3\nand 4. 251-g-2flV trades, 21-34; mediums,\n1 standards. 21-34.\nHow Is Business?\nSHOWING CURRENT BUSINESS ACTIVITY COMPARED WTTH\nTHE SAME WEEK A YEAR AGO.\nOCT. I NOV! D^c~ JAN rtn maw j ap. m.t juni IjulyIaug siptcmw\n1936 1937 \u201c~T~~ 1\nt 1-^\n40' Business\n_10* \u2014|-1\nJ GENERAL BUSINESS ACTIVITY for the country Indicated by Bank Dablta outside\nN Y. City. Shaded areaa show week ol activity above the corresponding week of the\nprevious year. Black areaa indicate declines from same weeks twelve months earlier.\nACTIVITY BY FEDERAL RESERVE DISTRICTS\nCheek Treesaetteas aaassrsf with the same weak a vast ala\ni1\nI\nLEADING BAROMETERS\nrr 1 Showing Trend of Important Factors _\nn _ 7\u00bb uiumgt\nCl rrewnt Trend From Year Ago\nr Business in Dollars (Checks Cashed) Downward 4- 9 0\nrj Employment (Dept, of Labor). Upward i li st\ns Wages (Dept, of Labor). Downward I 26 1\ne Cost of Living (Ind. Conf. Board)... Steady 4. 4\nP Wholesale Prices (Fisher\u2019s Indei). Downward 4- 9 4\ny Agricultural Prices (Bureau of Labor) Downward 4- 3 0\nMovement of Goods (Car Loadings). Downward 4- 4 2\ne Retail Trade (Fed. Res. Board). Downward 4. 1 s\n,s Building Contracts (F. W. Dodge).. Downward 4- 3.3\ni. Failures (Dun\u2019s). Downward 73\nit Bond Prices (Dow-Jonea). Downward 3.7\nd Stock Prices (Composite Dow-Jones) Downward _ 1V1\ny _Stock_Mkt. VoL (Shares Traded)... Upward 4. 3^0\nAH righu rtuntd, Cmbriigt Amdaiu, BoUm\n\nSTOCKS GO DOWN\nSI TO $4 A SHARE\nIN HEAVY TRADING\nSteels, Implements, Coppers\nand Specialties Weak.\nSome New Lows Set.\nU. S. BONDS RESISTANT\nBUT CORPORATES EASE\nViews Differ on Effect of Roosevelt\nI Address\u2014Unloading by Large\nHolders Reported.\nwhat stocks did.\nSal. Fri.\nAdvances __ _\nDeclines _ S7j 470\nUnchanged _iort jfin\nTotal issues_ 739 779\nBY FREDERICK GARDNER,\nAssociated Press Financial Writer.\nNEW YORK, September 18.\u2014Stocks\ntumbled through support levels in to\nday's brief market, many crashing to\nnew post-depression bottoms for losses\nof 1 to 4 points generally. There was a\nhandful of wider setbacks.\nFew issues escaped the selling that\nat one time put the ticker tape a min\nute or so behind floor transactions.\nDealings slowed in recovery periods.\nSteels were notably weak, along\nwith coppers, farm implements and\nspecialties. Rails showed some come\nback near the close, and utilities, on\nthe whole, were only fractionally in\narrears.\nOpinion was mixed in the financial\nsector as to how much of the down\nturn was inspired by the President\u2019s\nConstitution day speech.\nIt was pointed out by some, however,\nthat the Chief Executive's remarks\nwere hardly new or startling, being\nlargely reiteration of the principles he\nhas maintained all along.\nOther Factors Watched.\nMost brokers thought the renewal of\nthe downswing was due mainly to\nother influences, including business\ndoubts, foreign war clouds and indica\ntions important stockholders have been\ngetting \"out from under\" during the\nj last several months.\nThe Associated Press average of 60\nstocks fell 1.5 points to 57.7, equaling\nj the low mark for'this index since April\n29 last year. Transfers totaled 703.370\nshares, compared with 1,404.120 last\nSaturday, which was the largest two\nhour volume since March 6.\nHelping to depress steels were dwin\ndling backlogs for this industry and\nsigns mill operations are due for a\nrecession soon if new orders do not\nappear.\nCoppers, of course, were still under\nthe spell of sliding prices for the .ex\nport metal and talk of slicing the do\nmestic rate because of increased pro\nduction and decreasing consumption.\nAllied Chemical shares, on a few\nI sales, toppled 12 points to 192. Losers\nof sizable but lesser amounts were\nUnited States Steel at 90\u20188, Bethle\nhem, 76: Chrysler, 94 ?s; General Mo\ntors. 49\u2019,: Anaconda, 43; Kennecott,\n49>8; Texas Corp, 50; New York Cen\ni tral, 27>2; Santa Fe. 60; Great North\nern. 39'2; Westinghouse, 1251,; J. I.\nCase, 138 h; International Harvester.\n93 >x; United States Rubber, 40*s;\nUnion Carbide, 90; Sears-Roebuck,\n78 General Electric, 45'\u2019,; Electric\nPower <fc Light, 16; Paramount, 18;\nSocon.v Vacuum, 1818; Du Pont, 148'2,\nand Marshall Field, 19>2.\nBond Market Eases.\nA dropping bond market was bol\nstered somewhat by a slight stiffening\nin Federal loans. Gains, which were\nin the majority, ranged up to 5-32 of\na point while losses were held to\naround 4-32.\nTurnover in Federals was approxi\nmately $130,000 face amount, com\npared with around $150,000 Friday.\nCorporate ratings slipped from\nfractions to around 3 points lower on\nlight dealings. Lower priced and de\nfaulted rail liens led the decline. The\nAssociated Press averages for 20 rails\ndropped .3 of a point to 86.2.\nAmong some of the widest declines\nin this group were New Haven con\nvertible 6s at 32, off 2%-; Alleghany\n5s stamped at 42, off 2; Great North\nern 4s at 115%, off 134, and Southern\nPacific refunding 4s at 103%., off 1%,\nIndustrial liens wobbled fraction\nally lower, dropping .1 of a point in\nthe averages .to 101.9, while utilities\nran into moderate selling forcing them\ndown .2 of a point in the averages to\nthe lowest level since January^1935.\nCurb Shares Join Drop,\nThe curb market declined fractions\nto around 4 points in moderately ac\ntive trading. Some of the widest\nrecessions appeared in the oil group.\nGulf Oil fell 2% to 48% and Creole\nPetroleum was down a point to 28%.\nSunray Oil and International Petro\nleum were fractionally lower.\nAs stocks moved lower in sympathy\nwith a depressed \u201cBig Board\" some\nof the higher-priced shares were dealt\nsharp setbacks. Aluminum Co. of\nAmerica declined 4 to 123 and Elec\ntric Bond Share preferred dropped\n3 to 66.\nThe utility division showed many\nfractional losses including American\nGas tk Electric at 29%, off\nAmerican Superpower at 1%, off\nElectric Bond Share at 1334, off\nand United Gas at 7%, off\nFOREIGN EXCHANGES.\nNEW YORK, S\"Ptember is iA\u2019i.\u2014Minor\nvariations In leadinR currency units were\nrecorded in quiet foreign exchange dealings\ntoday.\nThe pound sterling dipped of a cent.\n'he French franc was unchanged. Nether\nlands guilders added .01 of a cent the\nSwiss franc was .00% of a cent lower and\ni the Canadian dollar remained at yester\nj day's closing level.\nThe dollar sagged of a cent In Lon\ndon. closing at 4 1(0(o the pound. There\nwas no trading in Paris.\nClosing New York rates follow:\nGreat Britain in dollars, others in crnts.\nGreat Britain, demand. 4.00: cables. 4.00:\nOil-day bills. 4.0.\">%. France, demand.\n.'l..'ISrl4; cables. Italy, demand.\n6.26%; cables. 5 '10',4.\nDemands Belgium 16.83: Germany,\nfree 40.13; registered. 21.55; travel.\n26.05: Holland 55.10 Norway. 24.03.\nSweden. 25.58: Denmark. 22.15: Finland.\n2.20: Switzerland, 22.06%; Spain, un\nquoted; Portugal 4.52%: Greece .01;\nPoland 18.03: Czechoslovakia 3.40%;\nYugoslavia 2.33: Austria. 18.R7n: Hun\ngary. 10.75: Rumania .76: Argentina\n31.05 n: Brazil. 8,80%n: Tokio. 28.08\nShtngnal, 20.05: Hon* Kong. 3! 11: Mex\nlco City 27.85: Montreal in New York,\n100.on. New York In Montreal. 100.00.\nc\u2014Nominal.\n1\n_CURBING THE RECKLESS DRIVER.\nCONFIDENCE HURT\nBusiness Morale Has Met\nSharp Setback, Says\nStandard Statistics.\nSpecial Dispatch td The Star.\nNEW YORK, September 18.\u2014In its\nweekly summary of the general busi\nness situation, the Standard Statistics\nCo. of New York currently comments\nas follows:\n\"Business morale has suffered a\nsharp setback in the recent past, re\nflecting not only the collapse in stock\nprices, but also the fear that this in\nturn is due to the increasing burdens\nplaced by the Government on the at\ntainment of adequate profits.\n\"While business volumes have re\nceded irregularly from the peaks at\ntained last Spring, activity in most\nmajor industries has been sustained\nat levels well above those of 1936 in\nevery month of the current year to\ndate. However, this reflects to an\nimportant degree the heavy backlogs\nof unfilled orders accumulated in many\nindustries, and the delivery delays in\nothers due to strikes. Activity was\nwell enough sustained during the Sum\nmer months to reduce unfilled orders\nsharply in most lines and to fill ac\ncumulated needs resulting from strikes.\nConsequently, the stimulus for a fur\nther expansion in volume, or even for\nthe maintenance of present rates in\nmany lines, must come from new\norders.\n\"War fears have provided a strong\nretarding influence on business, re\ncently. Declining commodity prices\nalso have tended to cause conserva\ntive policies, largely because of the\nfear that lower farm products prices\nwill be reflected in slower buying in\nthe agricultural districts. Even great\ner concern has been felt over the dis\nappointing performance of the build\ning industry, where high costs have\nforestalled the rapid expansion which\ncould have provided the basis for a\ncontinuation of the broad recovery in\nbusiness generally for an indefinite\nperiod.\n\"Estimates of probable business vol\nume in the latterwnonths of 1937 have\nbeen toned down in consequence of\nthese developments, even though it is\nstill probable that a moderately larger\naggregate volume of production will\nbe witnessed in the last four months\nof 1937 than in the similar period of\n1936.\"\nINSURANCE STOCKS\nJSFb2\u00a3&-J28SS8\nBid. Asked.\nAetna Cas (2a) __ 87 Hi\nAetna Ins (l.HO) 44 u tai/,\nAetna Life i.HOai _ _ oflv. .>a\nAm Equit tl.tidal _II 35 371,7\nAm Ins Newark (\u20194a) _ I j t, l*'3.\nAm Reins (.80*) 351* 371/.\nAm Reserve (lai _ _ 25 o(i'4\nAm Surety (2(4) _ 48 50\nAutomobile (la) -\u2019It 301*\nBaltimore Am (,20a) ft 14 ri,\nCarolina (1.30) 71 21o..a.\nCity of New York (1.20) _ 21'a *\u2019:i\nConn Gen Life (.80) 303. 3:\u2019>/.\nContln Cas (1,20) _ _ 24\nFid Dep (4ai _114 jin\nFiremen's Newark (.30) 10'/. 113;\nFrank Fire (la) 28\u2019. 30'/.\nGen Reinsur (3) 35'. u:3*\nGlen Falls (l.HO) \\7_IIIH 42 44\nOlob A- Rep 1.80a)_ 17 10\nGlobe A Rut __ 50 54\nGreat American (la) _~ 2014 .>4\nHanover (l.floi _ 30 'A 3314\nHartford Fire (2) _ 70'S 7-3>-,\nHome Fire Sec _, _ 2 '/a 31/.\nHome Ins (la) _ 31'\u00ab 331.\nHomestpad (1) __ 183\u00ab -'O'.\nKnickerbocker (.80) _ _ 13 15\u2019.\nLincoln Fire ____ 41. 43,\nMaryland Cas 43, 5*,\nMass Bond (3*4) _ 64 57\nMerc Ins Pr (.15*) _ H\u20182 7'i\nNational Fire '3) _ flo3.\nNatl Liberty i.20ai s>2\nNew Hampshire (1.tidal 4 5 4H'a\n1 New York Fire (,80a 1 lit \u2022\u2019I\nNorth River (1) 25 '\u2019rt'it\nPhoenix (2a 1 80 84\nProv Wash (1) ao'i 3\"'a\nRevere <P) I11 <l.30l -4 25'a\nRhode Island Ins (.20*1 7'a 8\u20184\nRossia Ins I \u20184* 1 7\u00bb4\nSt Paul Fire (Ha) _ _ 201 Va 208'4\n8nrinefleld <4'aal 114 117\nSun Life (11 '.ei _ HOO 650\nTravelers (lHi 446 455\nU 8 Fire (2) _ 60'4 52V.\nWestehester (1.20a) _ 82 34\na\u2014Also extra or extras.\nB\u2014Declared or paid so far thla rear.\n4\nMissouri Pacific\nRequests Voice in\nWestern Pacific\nBy the Associated Press.\nThe Missouri Pacific Railroad Co.\nasked the Interstate Commerce Com\nmission again yesterday for permis\nsion to intervene in reorganization\nproceedings of the Western Pacific\nRailroad Co. The commission previ\nously had refused to permit the in\ntervention.\nThe carrier said it had spent $19,\n708,237 on the physical properties\nof the Pueblo transcontinental route.\nIt also contended that present re\norganization plans might result In\ncontrol of the Western Pacific passing\nto Interests \"antagonistic to the\nmaintenance and full development of\nthe Pueblo route as a competitive fac\ntor in transcontinental traffic.\u201d\nThe Missouri Pacific, the brief said,\nwould lose to competing carriers yield\ning net revenues of about $515,000 an\nnually if control of the Western Pa\nciflc passed to interests unfriendly\nor unwilling to co-operate with the\nMissouri Pacific.\nD. C. SECURITIES\n(Quotations by Johnston, Lemon Co.)\nYestertlay\u2019s closing bid and asked quo\ntations on Washington securities which\nare traded over the counter follow:\nBONDS. Bid. Asked.\nBarber Ross deb 4s '45 _ 75\nConsolidated Title 8s '51 loo\nD C PaDer Mill 1st 3s \u201948 25\nHamilton Realty 1st 5s \u201945 95 97\nMayflower Hotel Jst 5s \u201950 82'i 88\nNat Press Bldg 1st 3-5s '50 73 78\nRacquet Club 1st 5s '43 52\nWash Auditorium 1st Bs '44 75\nWash Properties 7s '62_ 49!i 62\nSTOCKS.\nAnacostia Bank _150\nAnacostia Finance _\nBarber Si Ross pfd (new) 7\nCity Bank 18\nColumbia National Bank 185\nConsolidated Title Corp pfd 42 45\nConsolidated Title Corp com B'a 8\nEast Wash Savings Bank 14)2\nFederal American pfd 32\nFederal American common I'2\nHamilton National Bank :)o>2 33\nInternationa! Finance Units 13\nMerchants Trans Si Stg pfd 18\nNational Capital Insurance 14\nNational Mtg A Invest pfd 2** 3*4\nNational Metropolitan Bank 240\nRaleteh Hotel common 32 37\nReal Est Mtg A Guar com 1\u20182\nSecurity Sav A Commercial 145 175\nSouthern Oxygen Co com 90\nUnion Finance Units 25\nUnion Trust Co 97 105\nWash Base Ball Club 35\nWash Convention Hall pfd 80\nWash Properties vtc _ 214 3'4\nCORPORATE EARNINGS.\nNEW YORK. September 18 i/pi.\u2014Corpo\nrate earnings statements released during\nthe week showing profits per common\nshare included:\nIB Weeks Ended August 15.\n1937 193B.\nChampion Paper A Fibre $1.41 $0.48\n8 Months Ended August 31.\nCaterpillar Tractor 4.39 3.29\n1 Months Ended July 31.\nLudlum Steel ..._ _ 2.07\nNational Container 1 02 34\nWestern Union Tel. 2.11 3.88\n12 Months July 31.\nAmerican Gas A Elec. __ 2.45 2 04\nAmerican Light A Traction 1.88 1.82\nDetroit Edison _ __ 8.83 8.81\n2B Weeks July 3.\nColumbia Broadcasting _ 1.48 1.22\nB Months June 30.\nCrown Cork Si Seal__ 1.70 2.27\nYear June 30.\nAmerican Ship Bldg. _3.62 1.31\nUniversal Leaf Tobacco 7.82 7.78\nVansdlum Alloys Steel_ 4.80 2.93\n\nAUGUST BUILDING\nBOLDS ABOVE 1336\nTotal in 37 Eastern States\nfor August Declines From\nJuly Level.\nEl the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, September l4.\u2014Aug\nust building construction awards in\n37 Eastern States totaled <385,104,100,\na decline of 11 per cent under July,\nbut a gain of 4 per cent over August,\n1936, F. W. Dodge Corp. reported to\nday.\nThe August volume was made up\nof $73,448,300 residential building\nawards, $117,209,800 non-residential\nbuilding and $94,446,000 public works\nand utility contracts.\nAbout two-thirds of the July to\nAugust decline was due to decrease\nin the amount of public-financed work,\nT. S. Holden, vice president, pointed\nout. Regarding construction of homes,\nhe said:\n\"Disappointment in the August resi\ndential building total is not *so great\nas would be Indicated by the con\ntract figures. Admittedly, residential\ncontracts fell below the total for the\ncorresponding month of the previous\nyear for the first time during the re\ncovery period, but the August, 1936,\nrecord was inflated by public housing\namounting to almost $32,000,000. In\nthe current month\u2019s record there was\nincluded less than $t;000,000 of pub\nlic housing. Consequently, private\nresidential building shows a 6 per\ncent gain over August of last year.\u201d\nWOOL TRADING QUIET\nAT BOSTON IN WEEK\nB| the Associated Press.\nBOSTON, September 18 (United\nStates Department of Agriculture).\u2014\nSelling was restricted in the wool mar\nket during the last week. Prices eased\nslightly on the small amount of busi\nness transacted. Many holders of\nsizable weights, however, refrained\nfrom offering their wools under exist\ning market conditions and made no\nchanges in nominal asking prices.\nOhio, fleeces were quoted steady to\nonly slightly lower on a greased basis,\nthe small sales being mostly on lighter\nshrinking lots offered. Which meant\na slight ease in scoured basis volume.\nFleece-basis quotations on combing\nOhio fleeces were mostly 40-42 cents\non fine delaine, 41-42 cents on staple\ncombing length half blood, 43-44 on\nthree-eights blood and 42-43 for quar\nter blood.\nCORN GRIND BELOW 1936.\nNEW YORK, September 18 OP).\u2014\nTne Corn Industries Research Founda\ntion reported a corn grind of 3,848,264\nbushels during the month of August\nfor products going into domestic use\ncompared with 6,762,739 bushels in\nAugust last year and 3,439,898 bushels\nin July this year.\nWeekly Financial High Lights\nBy the Associated Press. This week. Prev. week. Year ago.\nBrokers' loans __. $1,118,000 $1,146,000 $1,013,000\nHoldings U. S. Securities. 2.526,190 2,526,1,90 2.430,227\nGold reserve 9,129,890 8,830,890 8,38e!o71\nRediscounts. 23,198 23,559 J.011\nBank clearings... 5,829.512 4,434,738 6,456,984\nElectric output (kilowatt hours)\nweek ended September 11. 2,154,276 2,320,982 2,098,924\n(Final three ciphers omitted in above.)\nCar loadings, week ended Sept. 11- 711,229 804,633 700,184\nCrude oil products (barrels)- 3,642,400 3,692,550 3,020^850\nStock sales, N. Y. Stock Exchange... 7,623,110 9,266,560 6,110^002\nBond sales, N. Y. Stock Exchange... $43,387,550 $42,303,075 $59,251,000\nNew financing 20,216,552 5,723,000 103,559,000\nFederal Reserve ratio.. 80.0% 79.6% 79.3%\nSteel output rate.. 80.4% 71.6% 72 5%\nCall money rate. 1% 1% 1%\nTime money rat*. 1*4-1 Vi 144-1%% 144%\nCommercial paper 1% i%\n1 k\nRETAIL ACM\nHeavier Flow of Goods Con\ntrasts With Slower In\ndustrial Rate.\nSENTIMENT CONFUSED\nON BUSINESS OUTLOOK\nStock Slump, Cuts in Textile,\nShoe, Coal, Furniture Output*,\nand War Tension Blamed.\nBY THOMAS E. FLANAGAN,\nAssociated Press Pmaneiai Writer.\nA slower pace for the Nation's In\ndustry last week contrasted with a\nheavier flow of goods across retail and\nwholesale counters in many section*.\nHigher steel operations and decline*\nin freight carloadings and motor and\nelectricity output were projected\nagainst a background of mixed bust\nnesses sentiment.\nThis momentarily confused attitude\nof experts toward the outlook for trad*\nand industry had its origin in diver**\nfactors and some elements far removed\nfrom the scene of activity.\nThey included, analysts said, falling\nstock market prices, recent cuts in pro\nduction of textiles, shoes, coal and\nfurniture, renewed French fiscal\ntroubles and protracted strife in the\nFar East with its implicit threat to\nexport business.\nOn the bright side of the canvas*\nwere mentioned settlement of some\nlabor controversies, sustained farm\npurchasing power and the prospect of\nfaster steel and motor production.\nThe Associated Press index of in\ndustrial activity declined to 103 from\n104 6 the week before and compared\nwith 94 in the like week last year.\nRetail Gains Continue.\n\u201cRetail trade throughout the coun\ntry entered the mid-September period\nwith a continuation of the favorable\naspects which characterized it imme\ndiately following Labor day.\u201d said th*\nDepartment of Commerce in its weekly\nsurvey of 37 cities.\n\u201cObservers were encouraged by th*\nfact that wherever crisp Fall weather\nmade its appearance there was an im\nmediate response from shoppers\nwholesale trade began to reflect th*\nseasonal upturn in retail lines and th*\nshowing was encouraging.\u201d\n8teel operations rebounded to *0.4\nper cent of capacity following th*\nLabor day let down. Although it was\nunder the pre-holiday rate of M.l. a*\nreported by the American Iron ft Steel\nInstitute. It contrasted with 71.6 p*r\ncent in the week ended September 11.\nA month ago it was 83.2 per cent. Las*\nyear at this time it stood at 72 8.\nSteel Orders Increase.\nSteel trade circles noted a moderat*\npick-up in the flow of new business\nand cited the belief in well-informed\nQuarters that steel has been moving\nw.\u00bbuui^uuu nil iair rate ior\nthis season.\nIt was stressed steel use runs at a\nhigh rate In a number of industries,\nnotably can making and farm imple\nment manufacturing. Before long, it\nwas added, reinforcements will com*\nup from the rear when the automobile\nindustry gets under way with produc\ntion of new models.\nA sharp fall in motor output marked\nthe end of the 1937 season for major\nproducers. Outturn was 30,150 units,\ncompared with 59,107 the previous\nweek and 26.640 in the corresponding\nweek of 1936, Ward's reported.\nFollowers of the industry attached\nweight to the opinion of Alfred P.\nSloan, jr\u201e chairman of the board of\nGeneral Motors Corp. He said ho\nlooked for well-sustained sale of cafa\nin 1938. The industry at large will\nlikely have a good year, he held, owing\nto the fact the recovery movement has\nnot yet spent itself.\nFreight Loadings Down.\nFreight carloadings totaled 711,39#\nin the week ended September 11, tfio\nAssociation of American Railroad* re\nported. This was a drop of 11.6 per\ncent from the previous period, owing\nto the holiday interruption. The fall\nwas less than seasonal. Freight ship\nments were 16 per cent ahead of the\nlike 1936 week.\nThe decline on the week witnessed\nslower movement of all classifications\nof freight except grains in the Western\ndistrict, which rose moderately.\nRailroad men said hopes entertained\nbriefly in Wall Street for a settlement\nof pending wage negotiations were pre\nmature. At the same time, they ex\npressed the view higher operating cost*\nwere eating into profits.\nOutput of electric power in the week\nended September 11 totaled 3,154,\n276,000 kilowatt hours, the Edison\nElectric Institute reported. This was\nunder the preceding week, but with\nallowance made for the holiday, 6.3\nper cent ahead of the corresponding\n1936 week.\nFurther slackening in the demand\nfor power in the central industrial\ndistrict was again a prominent phase\nof the weekly report. In the latest\nweek power production in this region,\nallowing for the holiday, was 9.3 per\ncent ahead of a year ago, whereas\nin the preceding week the gain over\n1936 had been 11 per cent.\nLoan Total Expands.\nPutting the accent on the forward\naspect of trade trends, analyst* found\na bright spot in banking statistics.\nBusiness loans for the account of\ncommercial firms, industry and agri\nculture continued to expand. In the\nweek ended September 8, loans by\nmember Federal Reserve Banks in\n101 cities advanced *50,000,000.\nShares on the New York Stock Ex\nchange gyrated confusedly throughout\nthe week and met with selling at th*\nclose. Pressure on steels was pro\nnounced much of the time and was\nsaid to have somewhat mystified steel\nindustry observers who hold hopes of\na good Autumn business.\nA fall in copper shares also ar\nrested attention. It was touched off,\nexperts said, by a decline in th*\nprice of foreign copper to a new low\nfor the current move. Some said\nthe downturn in the price of the for\neign metal threatened to unhlng* th*\n(See TRADE, Page E-2.)\nA","height":"33640","width":"23844"}}
